00:28:24.610 --> 00:28:25.710 align:middle line:90%
What's your latest book?

00:28:25.710 --> 00:28:26.450 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: My latest book--

00:28:26.450 --> 00:28:27.170 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Excuse me.

00:28:27.170 --> 00:28:29.586 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Well, "Excuse
Me, Your Soul Mate is Waiting"

00:28:29.586 --> 00:28:32.400 align:middle line:90%
is my first book.

00:28:32.400 --> 00:28:34.320 align:middle line:84%
Then I had "Good
Date, Bad Date."

00:28:34.320 --> 00:28:36.560 align:middle line:84%
And then I did two memoirs,
"Diary of a Beverly Hills

00:28:36.560 --> 00:28:39.521 align:middle line:84%
Matchmaker," and the sequel,
"Hearts on the Line."

00:28:39.521 --> 00:28:41.020 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, "Excuse
Me, Your Soul Mate.

00:28:41.020 --> 00:28:42.440 align:middle line:84%
is Waiting" has
been a great book.

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:44.560 align:middle line:84%
It incorporates a
lot of attraction

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:45.944 align:middle line:90%
with finding your soul mate.

00:28:45.944 --> 00:28:47.860 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Tell me about
the Law of Attraction.

00:28:47.860 --> 00:28:48.260 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:49.910 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Oh, I'm a
big Law of Attraction girl.

00:28:49.910 --> 00:28:50.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:50.550 --> 00:28:52.760 align:middle line:84%
That's how I-- I co-create
everything in my life

00:28:52.760 --> 00:28:53.510 align:middle line:90%
with the universe.

00:28:53.510 --> 00:28:54.252 align:middle line:90%
It's so much fun.

00:28:54.252 --> 00:28:55.710 align:middle line:84%
And I'm sure a lot
of your viewers,

00:28:55.710 --> 00:28:58.360 align:middle line:84%
if they're watching Gaiam
TV, they're into that.

00:28:58.360 --> 00:29:01.060 align:middle line:84%
But it's really what you
think about you bring about.

00:29:01.060 --> 00:29:04.079 align:middle line:84%
It's raising your vibration to
match what you're looking for.

00:29:04.079 --> 00:29:05.620 align:middle line:84%
So of course, you
don't want to think

00:29:05.620 --> 00:29:06.940 align:middle line:90%
about what you don't want.

00:29:06.940 --> 00:29:10.386 align:middle line:84%
So when a woman has been
dating, maybe divorced,

00:29:10.386 --> 00:29:11.760 align:middle line:84%
maybe her husband
cheated on her,

00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:15.480 align:middle line:84%
so she's got these negative
ideas about dating, about men,

00:29:15.480 --> 00:29:18.690 align:middle line:84%
and upset about not
finding the right person.

00:29:18.690 --> 00:29:20.190 align:middle line:84%
Even though she's
out there looking,

00:29:20.190 --> 00:29:22.689 align:middle line:84%
but when you have that mindset,
you're not going to find it.

00:29:22.689 --> 00:29:26.530 align:middle line:84%
So once you switch
that switch and look

00:29:26.530 --> 00:29:29.867 align:middle line:84%
forward to meeting that person,
feeling good, being happy,

00:29:29.867 --> 00:29:31.950 align:middle line:84%
that's when you're going
to meet the right person.

00:29:31.950 --> 00:29:32.520 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: It happens.

00:29:32.520 --> 00:29:33.040 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Yes.

00:29:33.040 --> 00:29:34.140 align:middle line:90%
And it will happen, it will.

00:29:34.140 --> 00:29:36.630 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: And how difficult is
it to keep that relationship

00:29:36.630 --> 00:29:40.380 align:middle line:84%
going, in this era
where things happen?

00:29:40.380 --> 00:29:42.260 align:middle line:84%
And we've all gone
through those things.

00:29:42.260 --> 00:29:44.720 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: We
have to realize that,

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:46.720 align:middle line:84%
now that we're partners
and we're both working--

00:29:46.720 --> 00:29:47.940 align:middle line:90%
my husband and I both work.

00:29:47.940 --> 00:29:49.900 align:middle line:84%
We both have to split
the household chores.

00:29:49.900 --> 00:29:52.130 align:middle line:84%
We have a dog,
there's things to do.

00:29:52.130 --> 00:29:54.340 align:middle line:84%
And we can't just let it
fall on the other person.

00:29:54.340 --> 00:29:56.620 align:middle line:84%
And have compassion
for that other person.

00:29:56.620 --> 00:29:57.810 align:middle line:90%
Because we're working hard.

00:29:57.810 --> 00:29:59.000 align:middle line:90%
We've got a lot to do.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:02.490 align:middle line:84%
And it's easy to just snip
at each other and argue.

00:30:02.490 --> 00:30:04.620 align:middle line:84%
So of course, you're
going to have arguments.

00:30:04.620 --> 00:30:08.119 align:middle line:84%
But my husband always says, he
learned from somebody, the best

00:30:08.119 --> 00:30:10.410 align:middle line:84%
way to have a great marriage
is to have a short memory.

00:30:10.410 --> 00:30:11.718 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Yeah.

00:30:11.718 --> 00:30:12.415 align:middle line:90%
He' right.

00:30:12.415 --> 00:30:12.915 align:middle line:90%
He's right.

00:30:12.915 --> 00:30:14.331 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: And
as we get older,

00:30:14.331 --> 00:30:16.230 align:middle line:90%
that's not so hard to do.

00:30:16.230 --> 00:30:19.000 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: In this era
of social networking,

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.654 align:middle line:84%
people will text each
other more than they talk.

00:30:21.654 --> 00:30:22.570 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Oh, yes.

00:30:22.570 --> 00:30:25.730 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: People
will be on Facebook.

00:30:25.730 --> 00:30:28.120 align:middle line:90%
Things will be misunderstood.

00:30:28.120 --> 00:30:31.856 align:middle line:84%
I've gone to dinner
sometimes, as a matter

00:30:31.856 --> 00:30:33.230 align:middle line:84%
of fact, where
your husband plays

00:30:33.230 --> 00:30:35.790 align:middle line:90%
the piano in Beverly Hills.

00:30:35.790 --> 00:30:38.340 align:middle line:84%
And he's a good piano
player, by the way.

00:30:38.340 --> 00:30:42.480 align:middle line:84%
And I have seen
couples of two or four

00:30:42.480 --> 00:30:45.400 align:middle line:84%
sending text messages to
people, all four of them

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:46.260 align:middle line:90%
have their phones.

00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:47.080 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Yeah.

00:30:47.080 --> 00:30:49.740 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: And not one of them
is talking to each other.

00:30:49.740 --> 00:30:51.070 align:middle line:90%
Not one.

00:30:51.070 --> 00:30:53.660 align:middle line:84%
And they're just sending
their text messages.

00:30:53.660 --> 00:30:56.540 align:middle line:84%
What has that done
to relationships?

00:30:56.540 --> 00:30:58.400 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Well,
even myself, I'm guilty.

00:30:58.400 --> 00:30:59.983 align:middle line:84%
I mean, my husband
will get mad at me,

00:30:59.983 --> 00:31:02.850 align:middle line:84%
because I'm kind of
working seven days a week.

00:31:02.850 --> 00:31:05.109 align:middle line:84%
My clients can email
me or text me any time.

00:31:05.109 --> 00:31:06.650 align:middle line:84%
You know, I work
from my home office.

00:31:06.650 --> 00:31:07.620 align:middle line:90%
I'm very boutique.

00:31:07.620 --> 00:31:09.530 align:middle line:84%
And we'll be out to breakfast--
every Sunday morning,

00:31:09.530 --> 00:31:11.620 align:middle line:84%
we go for our Mexican breakfast,
and that's our time together.

00:31:11.620 --> 00:31:13.850 align:middle line:84%
We have a great Mexican
place in the Valley we go to.

00:31:13.850 --> 00:31:15.790 align:middle line:84%
And I'll be on my phone
answering something.

00:31:15.790 --> 00:31:18.030 align:middle line:84%
He's like, honey,
this is our breakfast.

00:31:18.030 --> 00:31:18.580 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Put the phone away!

00:31:18.580 --> 00:31:19.000 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Put that away.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:19.690 align:middle line:90%
Put that down.

00:31:19.690 --> 00:31:22.785 align:middle line:84%
And I'm like, then I
realize, that's pretty rude.

00:31:22.785 --> 00:31:23.660 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: He's right.

00:31:23.660 --> 00:31:24.610 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Yeah, he's right.

00:31:24.610 --> 00:31:25.658 align:middle line:90%
And I'm sorry, honey.

00:31:25.658 --> 00:31:26.514 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: But you're addicted.

00:31:26.514 --> 00:31:27.370 align:middle line:84%
You know, you're doing
your work and stuff.

00:31:27.370 --> 00:31:30.300 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: It's just so--
and I was doing it with some

00:31:30.300 --> 00:31:31.180 align:middle line:90%
friends this weekend.

00:31:31.180 --> 00:31:33.120 align:middle line:84%
And I thought this is
not, you know, right.

00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:34.000 align:middle line:90%
We went out dancing.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.320 align:middle line:84%
And I'm like, I'm
texting my clients.

00:31:36.320 --> 00:31:38.230 align:middle line:84%
And this is, put it
down and go dance!

00:31:38.230 --> 00:31:40.000 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Yeah,
have a good time.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:41.708 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: But it
can run first dates.

00:31:41.708 --> 00:31:44.260 align:middle line:84%
I've had people-- you cannot
understand the tone somebody

00:31:44.260 --> 00:31:46.942 align:middle line:84%
has, or if somebody
tells a joke in the text,

00:31:46.942 --> 00:31:47.900 align:middle line:90%
you might get it wrong.

00:31:47.900 --> 00:31:48.285 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Right.

00:31:48.285 --> 00:31:50.659 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: And I've had
people not meet because of it.

00:31:50.659 --> 00:31:53.050 align:middle line:84%
I have had people-- texts not
go through, they never met.

00:31:53.050 --> 00:31:54.842 align:middle line:84%
Or guys, especially
the younger guys

00:31:54.842 --> 00:31:56.800 align:middle line:84%
in their 20's or 30's,
they're so into texting,

00:31:56.800 --> 00:31:59.917 align:middle line:84%
they'll make their first contact
with a women through a text.

00:31:59.917 --> 00:32:00.500 align:middle line:90%
You know what?

00:32:00.500 --> 00:32:01.460 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: It's a sign
of the the times.

00:32:01.460 --> 00:32:02.280 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Pick up the phone.

00:32:02.280 --> 00:32:03.160 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: They don't
do that anymore.

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:03.790 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: We don't do it.

00:32:03.790 --> 00:32:05.745 align:middle line:84%
We're all hiding behind
emails and texts.

00:32:05.745 --> 00:32:06.120 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Well, I've
got to tell you,

00:32:06.120 --> 00:32:08.550 align:middle line:84%
in what I do with "Coast
to Coast" for example,

00:32:08.550 --> 00:32:10.790 align:middle line:90%
and then my personal life.

00:32:10.790 --> 00:32:13.750 align:middle line:84%
If I talked to
everyone who sends me

00:32:13.750 --> 00:32:18.240 align:middle line:84%
a text message during the
day, I would get nothing done.

00:32:18.240 --> 00:32:20.530 align:middle line:84%
The phone would be
ringing constantly.

00:32:20.530 --> 00:32:22.430 align:middle line:84%
And I was thinking
just a few days ago,

00:32:22.430 --> 00:32:24.870 align:middle line:84%
what life was like
before cellphones.

00:32:24.870 --> 00:32:27.265 align:middle line:84%
Before we even had the
big Motorola ones, right?

00:32:27.265 --> 00:32:28.140 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: I know.

00:32:28.140 --> 00:32:28.870 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: And you know what?

00:32:28.870 --> 00:32:29.490 align:middle line:90%
We got by

00:32:29.490 --> 00:32:30.050 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: We got along.

00:32:30.050 --> 00:32:30.780 align:middle line:90%
We got by.

00:32:30.780 --> 00:32:31.750 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: We did
what we had to do.

00:32:31.750 --> 00:32:32.350 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: We had
answering machines.

00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:34.690 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: We got back to
our office and took care

00:32:34.690 --> 00:32:37.060 align:middle line:84%
of our messages and
did what we had to do.

00:32:37.060 --> 00:32:40.380 align:middle line:84%
But nowadays, you
just try, one day,

00:32:40.380 --> 00:32:41.990 align:middle line:90%
keep your cell phone at home.

00:32:41.990 --> 00:32:42.620 align:middle line:90%
You feel naked.

00:32:42.620 --> 00:32:44.620 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: George,
when I'm out in the world,

00:32:44.620 --> 00:32:46.430 align:middle line:84%
sometimes I'll look
on the street and see,

00:32:46.430 --> 00:32:48.962 align:middle line:84%
everybody's down like this,
or like this, on the street.

00:32:48.962 --> 00:32:50.420 align:middle line:84%
I mean, every
other-- every person.

00:32:50.420 --> 00:32:53.750 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: In Nevada, they're
thinking of passing a law which

00:32:53.750 --> 00:32:58.180 align:middle line:84%
would make it illegal to
send text messaging or to use

00:32:58.180 --> 00:33:00.570 align:middle line:84%
your smartphone
while you're walking.

00:33:00.570 --> 00:33:03.130 align:middle line:84%
Because people will walk on--
they'll walk on the street

00:33:03.130 --> 00:33:05.770 align:middle line:84%
and get hit by a car,
because they're not looking.

00:33:05.770 --> 00:33:06.430 align:middle line:90%
It's crazy.

00:33:06.430 --> 00:33:07.388 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: And trip.

00:33:07.388 --> 00:33:09.050 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: So so
the social network,

00:33:09.050 --> 00:33:12.150 align:middle line:84%
though it has speeded things
up, in terms of information--

00:33:12.150 --> 00:33:13.720 align:middle line:84%
I know when Michael
Jackson died,

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:15.980 align:middle line:84%
the world knew
about it in minutes,

00:33:15.980 --> 00:33:19.060 align:middle line:84%
through social networking--
it also can destroy

00:33:19.060 --> 00:33:20.140 align:middle line:90%
a relationship, can't it?

00:33:20.140 --> 00:33:21.015 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: It can.

00:33:21.015 --> 00:33:23.566 align:middle line:84%
And it just disconnects
us from our relationships.

00:33:23.566 --> 00:33:24.940 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand,
there's things

00:33:24.940 --> 00:33:26.440 align:middle line:84%
like Skype, which,
I love, because I

00:33:26.440 --> 00:33:27.890 align:middle line:90%
have girlfriends in France.

00:33:27.890 --> 00:33:29.902 align:middle line:84%
I have girlfriends in
Canada and Chicago.

00:33:29.902 --> 00:33:31.360 align:middle line:84%
We sit there with
our cup of coffee

00:33:31.360 --> 00:33:32.901 align:middle line:84%
like we're sitting
in the living room

00:33:32.901 --> 00:33:34.980 align:middle line:84%
together, looking at
each other, on Skype.

00:33:34.980 --> 00:33:37.000 align:middle line:90%
And so that's just awesome.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.140 align:middle line:84%
So technology has the
good and bad sides.

00:33:39.140 --> 00:33:41.314 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Facebook
creates problems, as well.

00:33:41.314 --> 00:33:43.230 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: People are
on there, constantly.

00:33:43.230 --> 00:33:45.340 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Constantly,
they'll get messages.

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:48.720 align:middle line:84%
A married couple will see
the messages of someone

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:51.070 align:middle line:84%
who put something on
someone else's Facebook.

00:33:51.070 --> 00:33:51.700 align:middle line:90%
And then--

00:33:51.700 --> 00:33:52.950 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Or you
look at the status,

00:33:52.950 --> 00:33:55.033 align:middle line:84%
the relationship status,
if you're dating someone.

00:33:55.033 --> 00:33:56.087 align:middle line:90%
Oh no, he's still single.

00:33:56.087 --> 00:33:57.670 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: They haven't
changed it yet.

00:33:57.670 --> 00:33:58.660 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Still
hasn't changed the status.

00:33:58.660 --> 00:33:59.140 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Exactly.

00:33:59.140 --> 00:33:59.700 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: And then
you've got to block people.

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:00.460 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: That happens.

00:34:00.460 --> 00:34:01.626 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Unfriend them.

00:34:01.626 --> 00:34:03.145 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: So do
away with that too.

00:34:03.145 --> 00:34:03.560 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Then
you're all hurt.

00:34:03.560 --> 00:34:05.150 align:middle line:90%
I was unfriended.

00:34:05.150 --> 00:34:07.866 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: So do you deal with
that stuff, social networking?

00:34:07.866 --> 00:34:09.449 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Social
networking, yeah.

00:34:09.449 --> 00:34:11.836 align:middle line:84%
Well, sometimes, see, so I'm
trying to match somebody,

00:34:11.836 --> 00:34:13.960 align:middle line:84%
and then they'll go do
their investigating and look

00:34:13.960 --> 00:34:15.989 align:middle line:84%
somebody up on Facebook or
try to see more pictures.

00:34:15.989 --> 00:34:17.488 align:middle line:84%
And say, oh, no,
I'm not-- you know,

00:34:17.488 --> 00:34:19.040 align:middle line:90%
they're not my type, after all.

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:19.909 align:middle line:90%
And don't do that!

00:34:19.909 --> 00:34:20.909 align:middle line:90%
You've got to trust me.

00:34:20.909 --> 00:34:21.929 align:middle line:90%
I know these people.

00:34:21.929 --> 00:34:22.510 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Go.

00:34:22.510 --> 00:34:23.510 align:middle line:90%
It's only a date, right?

00:34:23.510 --> 00:34:25.999 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: You paid
me, let me do my job.

00:34:25.999 --> 00:34:27.679 align:middle line:90%
Yes, go.

00:34:27.679 --> 00:34:30.560 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: How many dates do you
give someone for whatever fee

00:34:30.560 --> 00:34:31.520 align:middle line:90%
they end up giving you?

00:34:31.520 --> 00:34:34.280 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Well, usually
someone will join for a year.

00:34:34.280 --> 00:34:36.292 align:middle line:84%
And I give one to
two matches a month.

00:34:36.292 --> 00:34:38.250 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, if somebody
is really easy to match,

00:34:38.250 --> 00:34:42.335 align:middle line:84%
like they're just easier, let's
say, tall, dark, and handsome,

00:34:42.335 --> 00:34:43.960 align:middle line:84%
and every woman would
want to meet him.

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:45.960 align:middle line:84%
I'll match him a lot
more, just because--

00:34:45.960 --> 00:34:49.427 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: And how do you
solicit the women for him?

00:34:49.427 --> 00:34:51.260 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Well, I
have a large database.

00:34:51.260 --> 00:34:52.190 align:middle line:90%
I've been doing it a long time.

00:34:52.190 --> 00:34:53.935 align:middle line:84%
So I have over 300
women in the database.

00:34:53.935 --> 00:34:55.060 align:middle line:90%
And then i have recruiters.

00:34:55.060 --> 00:34:57.180 align:middle line:84%
I have other matchmakers
I network with.

00:34:57.180 --> 00:35:00.050 align:middle line:84%
The women in my database,
if they like my service,

00:35:00.050 --> 00:35:01.347 align:middle line:90%
they send their friends.

00:35:01.347 --> 00:35:03.680 align:middle line:84%
And so there's women coming
to me every week, new women.

00:35:03.680 --> 00:35:05.790 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Are there any
women who are frustrated,

00:35:05.790 --> 00:35:09.670 align:middle line:84%
who say to you, stop
sending me these guys?

00:35:09.670 --> 00:35:10.741 align:middle line:90%
Or anything like that?

00:35:10.741 --> 00:35:13.240 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: No, but sometimes
they'll take a little break.

00:35:13.240 --> 00:35:15.580 align:middle line:84%
I had one woman
tell my recruiter,

00:35:15.580 --> 00:35:18.600 align:middle line:84%
she says-- I set her
up with a great guy.

00:35:18.600 --> 00:35:21.187 align:middle line:84%
Texting, they messed
up, didn't meet.

00:35:21.187 --> 00:35:22.520 align:middle line:90%
And then I emailed my recruiter.

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:23.780 align:middle line:84%
I said, what's going
on with this girl?

00:35:23.780 --> 00:35:25.238 align:middle line:84%
And she says, oh,
I just called her

00:35:25.238 --> 00:35:27.151 align:middle line:84%
and she said that
God told her that she

00:35:27.151 --> 00:35:28.400 align:middle line:90%
shouldn't be dating right now.

00:35:28.400 --> 00:35:28.835 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Ooh.

00:35:28.835 --> 00:35:30.959 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: I said, better
listen to that big man

00:35:30.959 --> 00:35:31.815 align:middle line:90%
upstairs.

00:35:31.815 --> 00:35:32.620 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: If that's
what he's saying.

00:35:32.620 --> 00:35:34.030 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: If that's what
he's saying, take a break.

00:35:34.030 --> 00:35:35.946 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: If that's what
he's saying, exactly.

00:35:35.946 --> 00:35:37.560 align:middle line:84%
What advice would
you give the people

00:35:37.560 --> 00:35:39.710 align:middle line:90%
who want to meet someone.

00:35:39.710 --> 00:35:41.240 align:middle line:84%
They might not
have the resources

00:35:41.240 --> 00:35:43.060 align:middle line:84%
to go through a
matchmaker, like yourself.

00:35:43.060 --> 00:35:43.890 align:middle line:90%
What they do?

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:45.240 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Well, you can
get my book, "Excuse Me,

00:35:45.240 --> 00:35:47.641 align:middle line:84%
Your Soul Mate is Waiting,"
and that will take you right

00:35:47.641 --> 00:35:48.140 align:middle line:90%
through it.

00:35:48.140 --> 00:35:50.200 align:middle line:84%
And you don't need to
go through a matchmaker.

00:35:50.200 --> 00:35:53.110 align:middle line:84%
A matchmaker is not for
everyone, it really isn't.

00:35:53.110 --> 00:35:54.597 align:middle line:90%
But there are the online sites.

00:35:54.597 --> 00:35:55.680 align:middle line:90%
There are the meetup.coms.

00:35:55.680 --> 00:35:56.263 align:middle line:90%
Get out there.

00:35:56.263 --> 00:36:00.052 align:middle line:84%
If you like to dance, go to a
swing dance, or a salsa dance.

00:36:00.052 --> 00:36:02.010 align:middle line:84%
When I was living in
Chicago, and I was single,

00:36:02.010 --> 00:36:02.800 align:middle line:90%
I got into a rut.

00:36:02.800 --> 00:36:03.640 align:middle line:90%
I would go to work.

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:06.800 align:middle line:84%
Then I would want to come home
and watch movies with my dog.

00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:09.939 align:middle line:84%
And one of my girlfriends said,
Marla, every Wednesday night

00:36:09.939 --> 00:36:10.730 align:middle line:90%
I'm taking you out.

00:36:10.730 --> 00:36:13.720 align:middle line:84%
We're going to go to this
beautiful champagne bar.

00:36:13.720 --> 00:36:15.520 align:middle line:84%
They had a beautiful
one up on Rush Street.

00:36:15.520 --> 00:36:17.050 align:middle line:84%
And we went out
there every week.

00:36:17.050 --> 00:36:18.635 align:middle line:90%
And I did meet a guy.

00:36:18.635 --> 00:36:21.372 align:middle line:84%
I dated him for like five
months, just to get out.

00:36:21.372 --> 00:36:22.830 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't like
prowling around.

00:36:22.830 --> 00:36:25.800 align:middle line:84%
It was like going out for a
lovely drink and socializing.

00:36:25.800 --> 00:36:26.730 align:middle line:90%
And it was great.

00:36:26.730 --> 00:36:29.490 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Are there some
people who just don't need

00:36:29.490 --> 00:36:30.980 align:middle line:90%
a relationship?

00:36:30.980 --> 00:36:32.082 align:middle line:90%
Can they get by?

00:36:32.082 --> 00:36:33.040 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Oh, yeah.

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:35.120 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: On there
own, single forever?

00:36:35.120 --> 00:36:37.790 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Humans, we're
social creatures and we want

00:36:37.790 --> 00:36:38.900 align:middle line:90%
relationships.

00:36:38.900 --> 00:36:41.597 align:middle line:84%
But I think if you have great
friends, you have maybe a pet.

00:36:41.597 --> 00:36:43.180 align:middle line:84%
You know, you and I
are animal people.

00:36:43.180 --> 00:36:46.060 align:middle line:84%
I mean, my dog, I can get all
the hugs and kisses from my dog

00:36:46.060 --> 00:36:46.880 align:middle line:90%
that I need, right?

00:36:46.880 --> 00:36:50.140 align:middle line:84%
But we don't have to be
in a romantic relationship

00:36:50.140 --> 00:36:51.540 align:middle line:90%
every minute of our lives.

00:36:51.540 --> 00:36:53.340 align:middle line:84%
You know, people always
feel that, like, I

00:36:53.340 --> 00:36:54.760 align:middle line:90%
need to be in a relationship.

00:36:54.760 --> 00:36:57.770 align:middle line:84%
I think it's great to take
a break, even a few years.

00:36:57.770 --> 00:36:59.950 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: I only have
one sad pet story.

00:36:59.950 --> 00:37:00.140 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Oh.

00:37:00.140 --> 00:37:01.139 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Sad pet story.

00:37:01.139 --> 00:37:04.180 align:middle line:84%
When I was a kid, I had
a little baby turtle.

00:37:04.180 --> 00:37:08.080 align:middle line:84%
In those days, they sold
turtles at the stores.

00:37:08.080 --> 00:37:11.030 align:middle line:84%
And they don't anymore,
because of salmonella.

00:37:11.030 --> 00:37:12.540 align:middle line:90%
Well, you know what's funny?

00:37:12.540 --> 00:37:13.770 align:middle line:90%
We never got salmonella.

00:37:13.770 --> 00:37:14.490 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: We never
got it back then.

00:37:14.490 --> 00:37:17.073 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: You know, we did all
these horrendous, germy things,

00:37:17.073 --> 00:37:18.410 align:middle line:90%
and never got a disease.

00:37:18.410 --> 00:37:21.870 align:middle line:84%
So I bought my little tiny,
it was a slider turtle,

00:37:21.870 --> 00:37:23.050 align:middle line:90%
tiny little green thing.

00:37:23.050 --> 00:37:25.149 align:middle line:84%
And I must have been
about eight years old

00:37:25.149 --> 00:37:26.190 align:middle line:90%
and I'm playing with him.

00:37:26.190 --> 00:37:28.010 align:middle line:90%
And he bit me.

00:37:28.010 --> 00:37:31.674 align:middle line:84%
And you know, they don't have
teeth, but he wouldn't let go.

00:37:31.674 --> 00:37:33.965 align:middle line:84%
And I'm looking at this turtle
on the end of my finger.

00:37:33.965 --> 00:37:35.505 align:middle line:84%
And I'm eight years
old, and I'm screaming.

00:37:35.505 --> 00:37:37.439 align:middle line:84%
It didn't hurt, but it
just didn't look right.

00:37:37.439 --> 00:37:38.230 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Yeah.

00:37:38.230 --> 00:37:40.230 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: And I didn't
know what to do with him.

00:37:40.230 --> 00:37:42.540 align:middle line:90%
So I'm waving my hand, you know?

00:37:42.540 --> 00:37:44.140 align:middle line:90%
And I flung him.

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:47.960 align:middle line:84%
And he, unfortunately,
let go and hit the wall.

00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:49.087 align:middle line:90%
And that was it for him.

00:37:49.087 --> 00:37:49.920 align:middle line:90%
That's my sad story.

00:37:49.920 --> 00:37:51.650 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: I have
a sad turtle story.

00:37:51.650 --> 00:37:54.386 align:middle line:84%
When I was four years old, my
little brother was like one.

00:37:54.386 --> 00:37:56.260 align:middle line:84%
And I had two of those
little slider turtles,

00:37:56.260 --> 00:37:57.218 align:middle line:90%
with the little island.

00:37:57.218 --> 00:37:58.900 align:middle line:84%
You know, with the
little palm tree.

00:37:58.900 --> 00:37:59.770 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: With a
plastic palm tree.

00:37:59.770 --> 00:38:00.730 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: And I loved
those little turtles.

00:38:00.730 --> 00:38:02.080 align:middle line:84%
And then my brother
was on a walker.

00:38:02.080 --> 00:38:03.100 align:middle line:90%
And he would walk around.

00:38:03.100 --> 00:38:04.558 align:middle line:84%
He went over to
one of the turtles,

00:38:04.558 --> 00:38:07.165 align:middle line:84%
picked it up and bit
its leg, and it died.

00:38:07.165 --> 00:38:08.300 align:middle line:90%
And my mom, says--

00:38:08.300 --> 00:38:09.980 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: I used
to breed hamsters.

00:38:09.980 --> 00:38:12.110 align:middle line:90%
I was a boy scientist.

00:38:12.110 --> 00:38:16.430 align:middle line:84%
I was into chemistry, rocketry,
the bizarre, the paranormal,

00:38:16.430 --> 00:38:18.302 align:middle line:90%
that's what happened to me.

00:38:18.302 --> 00:38:21.270 align:middle line:84%
I decided I wanted
to breed hamsters.

00:38:21.270 --> 00:38:24.430 align:middle line:90%
So I did it right.

00:38:24.430 --> 00:38:28.270 align:middle line:84%
I had it down to the moment
the little tiny hamster

00:38:28.270 --> 00:38:30.210 align:middle line:90%
got pregnant.

00:38:30.210 --> 00:38:32.980 align:middle line:84%
14 days later, she
had her little litter.

00:38:32.980 --> 00:38:33.810 align:middle line:90%
It was amazing.

00:38:33.810 --> 00:38:35.230 align:middle line:90%
I even built them a cage.

00:38:35.230 --> 00:38:37.100 align:middle line:90%
I made one mistake.

00:38:37.100 --> 00:38:40.520 align:middle line:84%
I didn't realize how
small the hamsters

00:38:40.520 --> 00:38:42.480 align:middle line:90%
were when they were born.

00:38:42.480 --> 00:38:46.480 align:middle line:84%
And so I built it
with the screen bigger

00:38:46.480 --> 00:38:47.710 align:middle line:90%
than the hamsters.

00:38:47.710 --> 00:38:51.870 align:middle line:84%
The mother couldn't get out,
but the little babies could.

00:38:51.870 --> 00:38:53.720 align:middle line:84%
And my father,
God rest his soul,

00:38:53.720 --> 00:38:55.510 align:middle line:90%
would always go downstairs.

00:38:55.510 --> 00:38:58.350 align:middle line:84%
And that was where he would
shave and take his shower

00:38:58.350 --> 00:39:00.990 align:middle line:84%
and everything else
before he went to work.

00:39:00.990 --> 00:39:04.990 align:middle line:84%
And one morning, I
heard him screaming.

00:39:04.990 --> 00:39:07.440 align:middle line:90%
Screaming.

00:39:07.440 --> 00:39:11.230 align:middle line:84%
He had smashed baby hamsters
on the bottom of his foot.

00:39:11.230 --> 00:39:12.150 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Oh!

00:39:12.150 --> 00:39:14.210 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: They had crawled out.

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:17.400 align:middle line:84%
And I don't know
why we're talking

00:39:17.400 --> 00:39:19.610 align:middle line:84%
about this, when we're
talking about dating.

00:39:19.610 --> 00:39:20.670 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: You are--

00:39:20.670 --> 00:39:23.420 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: But you know,
things like that happen.

00:39:23.420 --> 00:39:26.164 align:middle line:84%
Anyways, let's take some
questions for Marla.

00:39:26.164 --> 00:39:27.580 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: No
more sad stories.

00:39:27.580 --> 00:39:28.010 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: That's right.

00:39:28.010 --> 00:39:28.850 align:middle line:90%
Who's got some more?

00:39:28.850 --> 00:39:30.540 align:middle line:84%
We've got a couple
more questions

00:39:30.540 --> 00:39:32.170 align:middle line:90%
that we need from you.

00:39:32.170 --> 00:39:34.400 align:middle line:90%
There you go, ma'am.

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:37.430 align:middle line:84%
>> AUDIENCE: How problematic do
you find people's self-esteem

00:39:37.430 --> 00:39:40.470 align:middle line:84%
issues to be in matching
them with other people?

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:45.550 align:middle line:84%
Because it feels like they would
have unrealistic expectations

00:39:45.550 --> 00:39:50.872 align:middle line:84%
and needs that would hinder
their finding the right person.

00:39:50.872 --> 00:39:52.580 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Self-esteem
is a big issue,

00:39:52.580 --> 00:39:56.110 align:middle line:84%
because a lot of people,
well, especially women,

00:39:56.110 --> 00:39:59.980 align:middle line:84%
we tend to look for a guy
to complete us or save us.

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:04.160 align:middle line:84%
We women value ourselves
based on our relationships.

00:40:04.160 --> 00:40:07.350 align:middle line:84%
And men get their
self-esteem from their work,

00:40:07.350 --> 00:40:09.230 align:middle line:90%
from their careers.

00:40:09.230 --> 00:40:12.550 align:middle line:90%
So it plays a lot into it.

00:40:12.550 --> 00:40:14.300 align:middle line:84%
That's why I always
say, work on yourself.

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:17.767 align:middle line:84%
Do as much introspection and
work on yourself as you can.

00:40:17.767 --> 00:40:19.600 align:middle line:84%
But you want to be a
whole, complete person,

00:40:19.600 --> 00:40:22.800 align:middle line:84%
happy with yourself, before
you partner with somebody else.

00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:25.390 align:middle line:84%
Two people who are broken,
not happy with themselves,

00:40:25.390 --> 00:40:27.830 align:middle line:84%
coming together, that's
a recipe for disaster.

00:40:27.830 --> 00:40:30.350 align:middle line:84%
And that's why we
have a lot of divorce.

00:40:30.350 --> 00:40:35.290 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Can you fix a
situation that may have been

00:40:35.290 --> 00:40:38.980 align:middle line:84%
good, and that fell apart and
then you try to work it out,

00:40:38.980 --> 00:40:41.990 align:middle line:90%
and does it work?

00:40:41.990 --> 00:40:43.047 align:middle line:90%
Can you fix mistakes?

00:40:43.047 --> 00:40:44.255 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Oh, absolutely.

00:40:44.255 --> 00:40:47.910 align:middle line:84%
You know, we all mess
up in relationships.

00:40:47.910 --> 00:40:48.450 align:middle line:90%
We argue.

00:40:48.450 --> 00:40:50.110 align:middle line:90%
We have difficulties.

00:40:50.110 --> 00:40:54.090 align:middle line:84%
If you're both willing to work
on it, and there's counseling,

00:40:54.090 --> 00:40:56.550 align:middle line:84%
there are books, there's
things you can do.

00:40:56.550 --> 00:40:59.004 align:middle line:84%
I think it's worth-- unless
you're getting beat up,

00:40:59.004 --> 00:41:00.420 align:middle line:84%
or cheated on, or
somebody, right?

00:41:00.420 --> 00:41:02.750 align:middle line:84%
I think people should put
a little effort into it.

00:41:02.750 --> 00:41:03.690 align:middle line:90%
It's not just magic.

00:41:03.690 --> 00:41:05.250 align:middle line:90%
Like, oh I found my soul mate.

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:06.240 align:middle line:84%
Everything is going
to be perfect.

00:41:06.240 --> 00:41:07.370 align:middle line:90%
We do everything the same.

00:41:07.370 --> 00:41:09.800 align:middle line:84%
We cut our peas, you know,
the carrots the same.

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:11.260 align:middle line:90%
We both eat peas one at a time.

00:41:11.260 --> 00:41:12.890 align:middle line:90%
We like the same music.

00:41:12.890 --> 00:41:14.410 align:middle line:90%
It's going to be a dream.

00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:15.660 align:middle line:90%
I found my soul mate, no.

00:41:15.660 --> 00:41:17.360 align:middle line:84%
A soul mate might
be a person who

00:41:17.360 --> 00:41:19.440 align:middle line:84%
has to show you some
parts of yourself

00:41:19.440 --> 00:41:20.960 align:middle line:90%
that you need to work on.

00:41:20.960 --> 00:41:24.590 align:middle line:84%
With my husband, I have
needed to work on patience.

00:41:24.590 --> 00:41:25.840 align:middle line:90%
There's some things that I--

00:41:25.840 --> 00:41:27.090 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: I mean, do
you fight with him?

00:41:27.090 --> 00:41:28.550 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Yeah, he's Latin.

00:41:28.550 --> 00:41:29.190 align:middle line:90%
Hey, you know.

00:41:29.190 --> 00:41:30.620 align:middle line:90%
He gets a little feisty.

00:41:30.620 --> 00:41:31.510 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: You don't?

00:41:31.510 --> 00:41:34.350 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: Well, no.

00:41:34.350 --> 00:41:35.490 align:middle line:90%
Never.

00:41:35.490 --> 00:41:38.142 align:middle line:84%
But the thing is, when
we do have a fight,

00:41:38.142 --> 00:41:40.350 align:middle line:84%
and I would say more of like
a squabble, an argument,

00:41:40.350 --> 00:41:43.587 align:middle line:84%
a disagreement, what's
really interesting about us.

00:41:43.587 --> 00:41:45.920 align:middle line:84%
It's like 20 minutes later,
it's like it never happened.

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:46.885 align:middle line:90%
We don't dwell on it.

00:41:46.885 --> 00:41:48.010 align:middle line:90%
We don't bring it up later.

00:41:48.010 --> 00:41:48.280 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: You
don't have grudges.

00:41:48.280 --> 00:41:48.550 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:41:48.550 --> 00:41:49.830 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: No, we
don't keep grudges.

00:41:49.830 --> 00:41:51.400 align:middle line:90%
We have to kind of hash it out.

00:41:51.400 --> 00:41:54.545 align:middle line:84%
And he does have more
of that kind of uppity.

00:41:54.545 --> 00:41:55.670 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: He's spontaneous.

00:41:55.670 --> 00:41:56.919 align:middle line:90%
>> MARTENSON: He's passionate.

00:41:56.919 --> 00:41:58.070 align:middle line:90%
He's very kind of fiery.

00:41:58.070 --> 00:41:59.420 align:middle line:90%
But then he's very sweet.

00:41:59.420 --> 00:42:01.290 align:middle line:90%
So it works out.

00:42:01.290 --> 00:42:02.735 align:middle line:90%
And hey, it's not boring.

00:42:02.735 --> 00:42:03.060 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: All right.

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:03.970 align:middle line:90%
Let's take some more questions.

00:42:03.970 --> 00:42:06.011 align:middle line:84%
How about from some of
you single folks out there

00:42:06.011 --> 00:42:07.167 align:middle line:90%
in the audience?

00:42:07.167 --> 00:42:08.750 align:middle line:84%
>> AUDIENCE: Should
we, at some point,

00:42:08.750 --> 00:42:11.201 align:middle line:84%
lower our expectations
as we get older?

00:42:11.201 --> 00:42:12.700 align:middle line:84%
>> MARTENSON: Oh,
that's a good one.

00:42:12.700 --> 00:42:16.390 align:middle line:84%
I see some people clapping
over here, for that one.

00:42:16.390 --> 00:42:19.120 align:middle line:84%
You know, I think, as we
get older we kind of mature

00:42:19.120 --> 00:42:22.490 align:middle line:84%
and realize, people,
we're all going to age.

00:42:22.490 --> 00:42:24.310 align:middle line:84%
We'll get a little
gray or lose some hair,

00:42:24.310 --> 00:42:25.800 align:middle line:84%
maybe get a little
paunch, or whatever.

00:42:25.800 --> 00:42:27.008 align:middle line:90%
And that is not as important.

00:42:27.008 --> 00:42:29.970 align:middle line:84%
It's interesting, because when
I-- the women in their 20's,

00:42:29.970 --> 00:42:31.480 align:middle line:84%
they still want
a really hot guy.

00:42:31.480 --> 00:42:33.270 align:middle line:84%
You know, it's all
